BOTULISM, BOVINE - USA (CALIFORNIA) (02)
****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Botulism, bovine - USA (California) 980421223442
Date: Wed, 22 Apr 1998 12:45:13 -0700
From: John Adaska <jadaska@cvdls.ucdavis.edu>

The ProMED-mail posting has the details correct.
I can provide a little additional background however. The feeder on this
herd recalled finding a dead cat within a round bale of hay. The hay smelled
bad but it was still thrown into a mixing wagon along with several other
components of the TMR [cattle ration. The feed was mixed and then put out
to 4 of 10 pens on the dairy. Only the four pens that were given this load
of feed were involved in the massive die off. Early concerns focused on
other toxins and so extensive feed analysis was performed in the CVDLS-Davis
toxicology labs. The feed samples had very uniform concentrations of all
feed components suggesting very good mixing. No compounds of concern were
found to be present in toxic concentrations. Examination of affected animals
in the field and in the diagnostic laboratory in Tulare brought about the
suggestion that perhaps botulism was involved.
This is when the feeder was questioned and mentioned the information
provided above. A small amount of feed has been tested for botulinum toxin
and the toxin (I believe type C1) was found. Rumen contents from an affected
cow were analysed and cat hair was found.
Testing is currently underway in an effort to find the toxin in samples from
affected cows. Tissues from a total of 10 animals were examined and other
than a single case of Johnes disease and a couple of abomasal ulcers there
were no significant lesions noted. Five of those ten animals were given a
full necropsy in the diagnostic lab and 5 were necropsied in the field by
the veterinarian. We also had a hard time understanding how 400+ cows could
die with botulism in one event but the evidence for uniform feed composition
throughout the load of feed is strong and it takes only a small amount of
botulism toxin to kill a cow. The working diagnosis at this point is
botulism toxicity but it is largely a circumstantial diagnosis until such
time that we can identify the toxin in samples from the cows themselves.
--
John Adaska
California Veterinary Diagnostic Laboratory
Tulare Branch
e-mail: jadaska@cvdls.ucdavis.edu
[Thanks John. - Mod.MHJ}
